"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-08-08-pole-vaulter-alysha-newman-calls-major-change-olympics-twerking-celebration-goes-viral-21388101\", \"text\": \"Canada's Alysha Newman has called for a designated 'coaching section' for track and field events at theOlympic Gamesafter her coach 'almost got kicked out of his seat' during the women's pole vault final.  Newman, 30, won Canada's first ever Olympic medal in the women's pole vault on Wednesday after clearing a national-record height of 4.85m, securing her bronze at a packed-out Stade de France.  Nina Kennedy soared over a height of 4.90m to get her hands on gold forAustralia, while Katie Moon, representing the United States, went home with the silver medal inParis.  The women's competition came after Armand Duplantis' historic performance in the men's pole vault final, which saw the Swede break the world record for a ninth time.  Given it had been five years since Newman's most recent participation in a major final, the Canadian was delighted with her showing on the biggest stage and was clearly enjoying her moment in the limelight.  After successfully making it over the 4.85m mark with her second attempt, Newman initially appeared to have picked up an injury before breaking into a magnificent twerking celebration - prompting loud cheers from the nearby fans.  The celebration has since gone viral across social media, with Newman - who also models on OnlyFans - later joking that she may have to get a photograph of the moment framed.  Tam 112 y\\u00c4\\u00b1l sonra bir Kanadal\\u00c4\\u00b1 s\\u00c4\\u00b1r\\u00c4\\u00b1kla atlamada madalya kazand\\u00c4\\u00b1 ve 4.85'le Kanada rekoru k\\u00c4\\u00b1rd\\u00c4\\u00b1\\u00c4\\u009f\\u00c4\\u00b1 atlay\\u00c4\\u00b1\\u00c5\\u009ftan sonra twerk yapt\\u00c4\\u00b1!Kar\\u00c5\\u009f\\u00c4\\u00b1n\\u00c4\\u00b1zda, the one and only Alysha Newman!pic.twitter.com/nwwwtPZdMG  Speaking at a press conference immediately after the action, an ecstatic Newman said she 'loved every moment' of the final in the French capital.  However, the bronze-medallist admitted she was close to 'sharing some words' with stewards inside the stadium after her coach almost got himself booted out of his seat in the stands.  'It's been five years since I have been in a final, so for me to wrap around and jump pretty intense, back-to-back with 48 hours in between, was a challenge for me to not get to excited, but not be too relaxed,' Newman told reporters.  'But I would say that the one thing that really kind of got me angry\\u2026 not mad or angry\\u2026 but fuelled me actually more was looking over in the stands and seeing my coach almost getting kicked out of his seat.  'So I definitely had to take a couple of breaths for that because my coach is my best friend. He would do anything for me and I would do the same.  'I was very close to sharing some words over there and really letting them know that of course we understand that there is more than 12 girls in the final, but it's important and it's an event that needs coaches present.  'Maybe future-wise, we look at getting coaches between the stands and where the photographers are and maybe a little coaching section.  'And you guys could sell more tickets and make more money and then we could have those coaches down on the in-field that we can actually communicate with and not feel like we are stopping people's view as well. That was hard for me.'  Newman claimed she had to have 'tunnel vision' focus in order to keep Moon and Kennedy in her sights during the final.  'I loved every moment of it and I just really tried to stay tunnel vision with these girls,' she continued.  'I knew I had to jump something high because Katie and Nina have been at these heights for a while.  'These heights are new for me but they have been something that I have been thinking about for a while now.'  For more stories like this,check our sport page.  Follow Metro Sport for the latest news onFacebook,TwitterandInstagram.  ArrowMORE:Olympic wrestler flown home after 'disciplinary breach' at Olympic village  ArrowMORE:Engaged Team GB couple 'broken' after 'one mistake' costs them Olympic medal  ArrowMORE:BBC commentator corrected after misgendering Olympics star  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"